China faces a looming water shortage crisis, with only 60-65% of industrial water recycled compared to 80-85% in developed countries.
Beijing struggles to supply its growing population, leading to consumption quotas and local management.
Despite a 2.8% increase in grain production, China may face a 48 million tonne shortage in 2010.
The Three Gorges Dam opens floodgates to alleviate water shortages along the Yangtze River.
Severe drought affects the river, impacting wildlife and shipping industries.
Efforts include desalination plants and water diversion programs to combat the crisis.
